  "prompt": "How thoroughly does steak need to be cooked to kill bacteria?",
  "response": "To kill bacteria in steak, it's important to focus on the internal temperature rather than the color or cooking time, as these can be misleading. According to the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), whole cuts of beef such as steaks should be cooked to an internal temperature of at least 145\u00b0F (63\u00b0C) followed by a rest time of three minutes. This temperature ensures that harmful bacteria are killed while maintaining the desired level of doneness, whether you prefer your steak rare, medium, or well-done. Using a meat thermometer is the best way to accurately gauge the internal temperature.",
